# Project Safe Edit Rules

This project uses `codex-windows-safe-edit-guard` rules for Windows Codex Desktop safety.

## Editing rules

- Do not use apply_patch.
- Do not use Codex built-in file edit helper.
- Before editing, list files and plan, then wait for confirmation.
- Write files only through PowerShell or Python with explicit UTF-8.
- For non-ASCII content, read back and verify no ???.
- After editing, run git status --short and git diff --name-only.
- Do not commit or push unless user explicitly asks.
- Do not delete untracked files unless user confirms.
- Do not modify .codex / WindowsApps / Codex install / Cursor extension / AppData Codex binaries.

## Recommended verification

After any edit, report:

1. Files created or modified.
2. Commands used for verification.
3. Output of git status --short.
4. Output of git diff --name-only.
5. Whether any unexpected ??? was found.

<!-- safe-edit-guard-boundaries -->

## Boundaries and limitations

This is a workaround and guardrail, not an official Codex fix.

It does not repack MSIX packages.
It does not modify WindowsApps.
It does not replace OpenAI binaries.
It does not disable the Codex sandbox.
It does not guarantee that Codex Desktop will never show sandbox/helper dialogs.

It only reduces risk by avoiding `apply_patch` and Codex built-in file edit helper paths.

